 The extent of useful thing/valuable supply use inefficiencies in cotton production in 
 Pakistan's Punjab: an (online or paper form that asks for a job, money, admission, etc.) of Data Envelopment Analysis 
 Muhammad Shafiq, Tahir Rehman* 
 Department of Farming, The University of Reading, Earley Gate, P.O. Box 236, Reading RG6 6AT, UK 
 
 Received ll November 1999; received in changed form 22 December 1999; accepted 29 December 1999 
 
 Abstract 
 This paper tries to identify sources of useful thing/valuable supply use inefficiency for cotton production in Pakistan's Punjab. The use 
 of a non-parametric method, Data Envelopment Analysis (DEA), is developed to study the relative technical and allocative 
 (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) of individual farms which use almost the same  inputs, produce the same product and operate under similar facts or conditions (that surround someone). In the 'cotton-wheat' system of Pakistan, there are a lot of farms that are both technically and 
 allocatively inefficient. The use of DEA shows that the way of doing things provides a clear identification of both the extent and the 
 sources of technical and allocative inefficiencies in cotton production. However, both the (understanding/ explanation) of the farm level 
 results created and the projection of these results to a higher level require care, given the technical nature of the farming-based 
 production processes.Â© 2000 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 Keywords: Data Envelopment Analysis; Technical (wasting very little while working or producing something); Allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something); Cotton 
 
 1. Introduction 
 
 A few recent studies on the technical and money-based (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) of crop production in Pakistan, 
 especially for wheat and rice, have pointed out the 
 existence of a 'yield gap'. This 'gap' refers to the 
 difference in working well on 'best practice' and on 
 other farms operating with similar useful thing/valuable supply gifts under the same conditions (Akhtar et 
 al., 1986; Ali and Flinn, 1987; Hussain et al., 1991; 
 Khan et al., 1994). Surprisingly, these studies have 
 ignored cotton, (even though there is the existence of) it being the major export from 
 Pakistan. 
 The existing studies on technical and money-based (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) have used the usual parametric meth* Corresponding author. Tel.: +44-118-931-8480; 
 fax: +44-118-931-6747. 
 E-mail address: t.u.rehman@reading.ac.uk (T. Rehman) 
 
 ods to guess 'average' (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) only (Khan and 
 Maki, 1979; Ali and Flinn, 1987; Ali and Chaudhry, 
 1990; Ali et al., 1993; Battese et al., 1993; Parikh and 
 Shah, 1994; Parikh et al., 1995). The guess of 
 such 'average' (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) appears to ignore the argument that the study of the individual farm is more important to measure the  useful thing/valuable supply use (wasting very little while working or producing something), and that 
 the parametric way(s) of doing things provides not enough information for policy analysis (Kalirajan, 1984; Kalirajan and Shand, 1986). The research reported here supports the importance of studying the individual farm 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something), and it is the first study of its kind to have 
 used the non-parametric method of Data Envelopment 
 Analysis (DEA) for analysing the (wasting very little while working or producing something) of individual farms in Pakistan. 
 The paper begins with a brief introduction of (wasting very little while working or producing something) measurement and of the development of DEA. 
 The description of data sources happens before the explanation of the DEA model in general and the (detailed description of exactly what is required) 
 
