 of this model for cotton production. Next, the use of a 
 Cobb-Douglas type of production function for identifying the important inputs in the production process is 
 discussed before presenting the results of the technical and allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) analyses. Finally, the usefulness of the DEA model for examining the useful thing/valuable supply 
 use inefficiency of cotton production in Pakistan is 
 tested. 
 
 2. Measurement of (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 The (wasting very little while working or producing something) of production units is measured either by parametric or by non-parametric methods. The 
 first approach guesses the limits/guidelines of the production or cost functions (related to numbers). The second one, 
 in contrast, builds a linear piece-wise function from 
 scientific (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) of inputs and outputs, without assuming any good  functional relationship between the inputs and the outputs. The non-parametric 
 or 'frontier' method of measuring (wasting very little while working or producing something) was first 
 introduced by Farrell (1957) and since then a few 
 improvements and extensions have happened (see 
 Battese (1992) and Coelli (1995)). 
 Building on Farrell's work, Charnes et al. (1978) 
 have developed the fractional linear programming 
 method of DEA, which compares inefficient firms 
 with the 'best practice' ones within the same group. 
 It has been used widely for (wasting very little while working or producing something) studies for 
 both public and private organizations (see Seiford and 
 State of control (1990)). In the farming-based money flow/money-based studies books, however, only a few examples of the application 
 of DEA could be found (Haag et al., 1992; Shimizu, 
 1992; Cloutier and Rowely, 1993). 
 
 2.1. DEA 
 The DEA way of doing things has come to be named after 
 its originators and is referred to as the CCR model. 
 It involves improving a scoring function defined as 
 the ratio of weighted sum of outputs of a particular 
 production unit and the weighted sum of its inputs, 
 that is (wasting very little while working or producing something). This function is improved subject 
 to the condition that with any of the production units 
 included in the analysis, the value of the goal 
 function (accomplished or gained) cannot be more than I, suggesting 
 that the (producing a lot with very little waste) units will have a score of 1. 
 
 The DEA method is thought of as one ofthe most successful ways of doing things of analysis proposed by (people who work to find information) 
 in Management Science and Operations Research, as 
 is obvious by the wastefulness of its applications (see 
 Coelli (1995)). However, the original version of the 
 CCR model is not very convenient for a linear programme as it has more handcuffs, etc. than (numbers that change/things that change), making it hard to solve. Because of this, the 'dual' version of the 
 CCR model is more popular as the DEA model. The 
 technical details can be found in Charnes et al. (1978), 
 Norman and Stoker (1991), Charnes et al. (1995), and 
 Coelli et al. (1998). 
 
 3. The sample of cotton producers 
 The data were collected from a randomly drawn 
 sample consisting of 120 farms from the cotton-wheat 
 area of the southern part of Pakistan's Punjab. The 
 sample farms can be treated as a (a mixture of things that are all pretty much the same) group 
 for a few reasons. First, all of the farms are in an 
 area where technical and (related to scientific farming) practice recommendation domains are the same. Second, they are in 
 reasonable closeness to each other. Third, all of them 
 face uniform natural and market conditions and the 
 same (set of machines). Finally, all the farms have broadly 
 almost the same  types of soils. 
 
 3.1. (features/ qualities/ traits) of farmers and farms 
 Information such as the farm operator's age, his 
 educational accomplishment, the size of the farm family and 
 the number of family members involved in farming is 
 given in Table 1. Most of the farmers are over 25 years 
 old, with the age ranging from 20 to 60 years. The 
 family size is large and three-fourths of the farms had 
 more than nine members per household, and on nearly 
 half of the farms, at least two of the family members 
 were working as full time farm workers on farm. 
 Most of the farmers till their own land, but quite a 
 few rent added/more area to increase the operational size 
 of their holdings. The holdings are divided into three 
 categories: farms which are less than 5 ha, 5-10 ha and 
 greater than 10ha. All the sample farms have almost the same 
 types of soils that are ideal for growing cotton. Cotton 
 occupies 77-85% of the area on different farms and 
 this proportion is even higher on large farms. Small 
 farmers in the area keep milk animals needing/ordering land 
 
