 where}= 1, ... , 117 is the number of farms or Decision 
 Making Units (DMUs) in the sample, m=1 represents 
 cotton in the cotton-wheat system, i= 1, ... , 6 is the 
 number of inputs included in the analysis, Z0 is the 
 relative (wasting very little while working or producing something) score of the DMU, 'o', under study, 
 A j are lambda values that are the weights to be used 
 as multipliers for the input levels of a referent farm to 
 point to/show the input levels that an inefficient farm should 
 aim at to (accomplish or gain with effort) (wasting very little while working or producing something), Xij is the level of use for 
 the ith input on the jth farm, Ymj is the level of the mth 
 output on the jth farm, Your  is the level of the output on 
 unit 'o', and X0 is the vector of the levels of inputs 
 being used by the DMU 'o'. 
 The highest value of Z0 (:::;1) for the unit 'o' is 
 found by 'combining' the performance of all units being carefully studied. This is done in such a way that, for each 
 input, the combination of inputs does not go beyond the 
 inputs of unit 'o' and for each output and the combination of outputs is at least as great as that of unit 'o'. 
 On solving the model separately for each DMU in the 
 sample, the (wasting very little while working or producing something) scores ( &amp;lt; 1 for the inefficient 
 units and 1 for the (producing a lot with very little waste) ones) are established. A 
 score less than 1 means that a linear combination of 
 other units from the sample could produce the same 
 vector of outputs using lower levels of inputs. The 
 problem of returns to scale can be dealt with by using 
 the Banker et al. (1984) extension to the CCR model 
 as: (a) for constant returns to scale (CRS), the condition I; Ai 2: 1 is added; and (b) for (number or thing that changes) returns 
 to scale (VRS), the self-control/control device I; Ai = 1 is (forced (on people)/caused an inconvenient situation). 
 To get the (wasting very little while working or producing something) scores, a linear programming matrix was built which included input 
 and output data for each of the farms in the sample. 
 It was then used to test the (wasting very little while working or producing something) of an individual farm by substituting its inputs and outputs 
 into the vectors Y0 and X0 in Eqs. (2) and (3) above. 
 
 M. Shafiq, T. Rehman/Agricultural Money flow 22 (2000) 321-330 
 
 324 
 
 This 'iteration' or substitution was repeated 117 times 
 (three (something that's not part of the main group) farms were dropped from further analysis) to get (wasting very little while working or producing something) scores for all the sample farms. 
 For a firm to be (producing a lot with very little waste), two conditions must hold: 
 (a) that the calculated value of Z0 that is Z" must equal 
 1; and (b) all the slack (numbers that change/things that change) in the LP solution 
 must be 0 (Charnes et al., 1978). 
 
 5. Role of different inputs in crop working well 
 It is quite usual to (combine different things together so they work as one unit) some form of functional 
 analysis with the DEA model, mostly moving backward models, to identify those inputs that play a well-known/obvious role 
 in deciding/figuring out working well. (after that), the relative (wasting very little while working or producing something) of a production unit can be measured 
 (Charnes et al., 1978; Bowlin et al., 1985; Dyson 
 et al., 1990; Roll and Cook, 1993; Thanassoulis, 1993). 
 So, a Cobb-Douglas type of production function 
 was fitted to the data collected from the survey and 
 the results are discussed below. 
 
 5.1. Explanation of the (numbers that change/things that change) 
 The major inputs that are assumed to decide/figure out 
 the cotton crop output (kg/ha) include crop-watering/rinsing with water water (number per hectare), nitrogen (kg (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.)/ha), 
 phosphate (kg (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.)/ha), labour (h/ha), bug-killer 
 costs (Rs. per hectare) and tractor hours needed/demanded per 
 hectare for levelling, ploughing, planking and planting. The basic statistics related to these (numbers that change/things that change) are 
 presented in Table 2. It is clear that there is a wide difference/different version in both the input use and the cotton output. The 
 
 output received/got by some of the farmers in the sample 
 was three times as high as that (accomplished or gained) by others; 
 and there were wide differences/different versions in the levels at which 
 inputs were being used. There were large differences 
 in the use of nitrogenous (material that makes plants grow better) as some farmers 
 were using six times more (material that makes plants grow better) as compared to 
 others and some farmers did not use any phosphatic 
 (material that makes plants grow better). In preparing their fields for cotton planting, 
 some farmers use as few ploughings as two, while 
 some plough the fields 13 times before planting. Such 
 a difference/different version in the levels of inputs being used suggests 
 that possibly these levels represent a (running a business or organization very badly) 
 of useful thing/valuable supply use. 
 
 6. Results of the (related to numbers) guessed function 
 In Table 3, a very low value of the (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) R 2 
 (0.044) shows that the production function does not 
 explain a great deal of the relationship between the dependent and the (things that you control (like study times), that cause other things to change (like test scores)) as most of the 
 (numbers that change/things that change) had a non-significant effect on the increase 
 in cotton output. (numbers that change/things that change) like phosphatic (material that makes plants grow better) 
 use, labour and tractor hours used show negative 
 returns, suggesting an too much/too many use of these inputs. 
 So, the levels at which these inputs are being used 
 could be lowered without reduction in output levels. 
 These results in effect confirm the need for undertaking the analysis of the (wasting very little while working or producing something) of production using 
 a non-parametric method like DEA, as identifying 
 inefficient farms would suggest discovering the extent 
 by which their input use could be improved. What's more, when there is as much difference/different version in inputs used 
 
