 7.1. Use of DEA results to study inefficiency on an 
 individual farm 
 
 By using the results of the DEA model, it is possible to work out what is needed/demanded by inefficient farms 
 to become (producing a lot with very little waste). Take the farm DMU-70, with (wasting very little while working or producing something) scores of 57.97 and 58.78 under the CRS 
 and VRS ideas (you think are true), (match up each pair of items in order). For this farm, the 
 farms 40 (0.287), 54 (0.309) and 86 (0.382) are its referent units when CRS are assumed, while the DMUs 
 6 (0.043), 40 (0.246), 54 (0.316) and 86 (0.395) are 
 the referents when VRS are assumed. 
 The production practices of the DMU-70 and its referents are compared in Table 5, and clearly, the use of 
 inputs by the DMU-70 is 'excessive'. The 'excessive' 
 nature of the input use by DMU-70 is carried out when 
 the recommendations by the Central Cotton Research 
 Institute (CCRI, 1994) are carefully thought about/believed. According to 
 CCRI in this area, nitrogen plays the most in control/most common role in 
 deciding/figuring out cotton produce and phosphorus adds/gives 
 little, and to get best yield, there is no need to 
 plough the land more than four or five times. As is 
 obvious, this farm is not following the recommended 
 practices. However, this particular farm has a greater 
 number of land parcels (three) as compared to its 
 peers (DMUs 6, 46, 54, and 86) which are touching 
 
 327 
 
 farm holdings. This situation may have endangered 
 the chances of this farm becoming (producing a lot with very little waste). 
 The above comparison would suggest plans for 
 the DMU-70 to (give reasons for something) the use of its inputs. The 
 lambda values received/got from the DEA solution for this farm provide a (made up of different things) DMU which would produce 
 the equal level of output, but by using lesser levels of inputs as shown in Table 5. This information as 
 created by the DEA modelling approach is naturally interesting and the DEA model can be run to 
 examine allocative or money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) of useful thing/valuable supply 
 use on individual farms, as illustrated in Section 8. 
 
 8. Results of allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) analysis 
 The (understanding/ explanation) of allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) depends 
 on the ideas (you think are true) made about a farmer's behaviour. 
 Farrell (1957) assumed that cost minimization is the 
 basis on which a farmer's portion decision is taken 
 to get a given level of output and the allocative inefficiency is a farmer's inability to equate the ratio of 
 not important products of inputs to the ratio of their (pertaining to each person or thing) prices. Lau and Yotopoulos (1971), Schmidt 
 and Lovell (1979), and Kopp and Diewert (1982) have 
 assumed (money made/good thing received) making the most of behaviour and have defined allocative inefficiency as the failure to equate the 
 not important value product of inputs to their prices. In the 
 DEA model, however, the behavioural idea (you think is true) is 
 
