 Results of the guess of both technical and 
 allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) show that technically (producing a lot with very little waste) 
 farms were also allocatively (producing a lot with very little waste). However, some 
 units such as the DMU-101 and the DMU-111 were 
 technically (producing a lot with very little waste) but were not so allocatively. 
 
 8.1. Sensitivity analysis for an individual DMU's 
 allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 
 more hard to notice/skillful as the allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) is the proportion by which the costs of the levels of inputs on a 
 farm can be reduced without any loss in output. So, 
 an (wasting very little while working or producing something) score of 0.8 hints that the DMU concerned could reduce its costs by 20% by choosing a 
 more cost-(producing a lot with very little waste) input mix. 
 In measuring allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) of cotton production, the costs of individual inputs used have been guessed by using the actual prices paid by farmers. The 
 (numbers that change/things that change) belonging to the same category were combined 
 together to reduce the number of cost (numbers that change/things that change) in order to help analysis. The (numbers that change/things that change) defined were 
 expense (in Rs. per hectare) on (i) land (producing crops/helping something grow); (ii) cotton seed; (iii) thinning; (iv) inter-cultural 
 operations; (v) (material that makes plants grow better); (vi) crop-watering/rinsing with water; and (vii) bug-killer usage. The results as given in Table 6 show that, 
 assuming VRS, nearly 30% of the DMUs have an (wasting very little while working or producing something) score of 1. 
 
 The DMU-83 has the lowest allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 score of 56.67 (assuming VRS) and it can be used to 
 illustrate the use of sensitivity analysis for exploring 
 the avenues for improving the allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 The lambda values connected with the solution for 
 this farm show that the DMUs 30, 47, 54, 64, 84, 86 
 and 113 were its referent units (see Table 7). For most 
 of the inputs, the referent DMUs were spending much less than the DMU-83 especially on pest 
 control, (material that makes plants grow better), and (producing crops/helping something grow). Using lambda values of the referent DMUs, the targets which DMU-83 
 can aim at become allocatively (producing a lot with very little waste) and are presented in the last column of Table 7. This farm needs 
 to decrease its expense on bug-killer, crop-watering/rinsing with water and 
 land preparation operations. 
 
 9. Ending/deciding statements 
 The previous/coming before analysis points towards the existence 
 of a significant extent of useful thing/valuable supply use inefficiency on 
 cotton farms in the cotton-wheat production system 
 of Pakistan's Punjab. In many events, the quanti- 
 
