 M. Shafiq, T. Rehman/ Farming-based Money flow 22 (2000) 321-330 
 
 ties of inputs used were (without a good reason) higher than what 
 would be needed/demanded to reach their present levels of 
 crop output. By using the DEA modelling approach 
 for (wasting very little while working or producing something) analysis, it is possible to (accomplish or gain with effort) two 
 types of results. First, it is possible to identify the changes/recalculations that can be made in the use of inputs on 
 inefficient farms by comparing them with their 'peer' 
 farms. Second, the factors that can be moved around/misled and tricked to 
 (make small) the too much/too many use of inputs and because of this reduce 
 the costs of production can be established. However, 
 for a meaningful (understanding/ explanation) of the DEA results, it 
 is necessary to think about  (all of/every part of) recommendation domains for different production practices in particular areas, as without including all the (connected/related) 
 and important factors in the analysis, one cannot be 
 bold about the sources of inefficiencies. Anyway, the DEA approach has an undoubted edge over 
 the standard production function analysis for identifying the sources of inefficiencies on individual farms. 
 The DEA results are much easier to understand/explain and to 
 use for (asking lots of questions about/trying to find the truth about) avenues for improvements in 
 technology and useful thing/valuable supply use (wasting very little while working or producing something) on farms. 
 This exercise in using the DEA modelling approach 
 for measuring (wasting very little while working or producing something) has (showed/shown or proved) that there 
 was a high degree of allocative inefficiency, regarding 
 costs of production, on cotton-producing farms in Pakistan. However, the (wasting very little while working or producing something) scores for both technical 
 and allocative (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) increase with increase in the 
 number of input (numbers that change/things that change) included in the DEA model. 
 The real advantage of DEA modelling is that it allows 
 the (detailed description of exactly what is required) of a multi-product, multi-input firm 
 (Byrnes et al., 1987). The construction of the 'efficient 
 edge of something/unexplored area' for measuring the (wasting very little while working or producing something) is (accomplished or gained) without having to make any pre-assumption (related to/looking at/thinking about) the 
 hidden (under) functional form and the (related to studying numbers) errors 
 connected with the (detailed description of exactly what is required) of such a function are 
 also avoided. 
 
